England, United Kingdom","Mitford, Northumberland, England":"Mitford, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Warsop, Nottinghamshire, England":"Warsop, Nottinghamshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bartram","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and North German: variant of   Bertram  .","History: William Bartram, a Quaker, had a large farm near Darby, PA, when his eldest son, John, the first American botanist, was born in 1699. John conducted botanical experiments at his own farm in Kingsessing, PA, near Philadelphia."],"variants":[{"name":"Bartrum","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Bartram   (see   Bertram  )."]},{"name":"Bertram","meanings":["German, English (mainly in southeastern Scotland, of Norman origin), French, and Danish: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Bertram</i>, composed of the elements <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ + <i>hramn</i> ‘raven’. The raven was the bird of Odin, king of the gods, in ancient Germanic mythology. The personal name was common in France throughout the Middle Ages (especially in the form   Bertrand  ), where its popularity was increased by the fame of the troubadour Bertrand de Born (<i>c.</i> 1140–1214). The name was taken to England by the Normans in the forms <i>Bertran(d)</i>, <i>Bertram</i>, and <i>Bartram</i>."]},{"name":"Bartron","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Bartram  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Joane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, and so a doublet of   Joan .  This too was revived as a given name in its own right in the first half of the 20th century. It has to some extent been influenced by the independently formed combination <i>Jo Anne</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Johanne","meanings":["and Norwegian feminine form of   Johan ."]},{"name":"Joann","meanings":["From Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, and so a doublet of   Joan .  This too was revived as a given name in its own right in the first half of the 20th century. It has to some extent been influenced by the independently formed combination <i>Jo Anne</i>."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":15,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Joane Bartram was born about 1244, in Mitford, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Rowland Bertram. She married Robert de Sutton on 20 June 1265, in Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 5 sons. She died in 1274, in Warsop, Nottinghamshire, England, at the age of 31."},"et":{"Abt 1244–1274":"umbes 1244–1274","1244–1274":"1244–1274","–Female":"Surnud","1240–1274":"1240–1274","1266–1346":"1266–1346","1266–1318":"1266–1318","1266–1338":"1266–1338","1268–Male":"1268–Surnud","1269–Male":"1269–Surnud","1220–1260":"1220–1260","20 Jun 1265":"20. juuni 1265","1220":"1220","1274":"1274","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1338":"1338","1259":"1259","1269":"1269","1346":"1346","1268":"1268","Abt 1244":"umbes 1244","1266":"1266","1244":"1244","29 September 1266":"29. september 1266","1318":"1318","Haddon, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Mitford, Northumberland, England":"Mitford, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warsop, Nottinghamshire, England":"Warsop, Nottinghamshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1244–1274":"noin 1244–1274","1244–1274":"1244–1274","–Female":"Kuollut","1240–1274":"1240–1274"